\b 5) Remote Usage (Your PC as a Server)\b0\par
- Start the Flask app locally: python water_harvest_dashboard.py\par
- Ensure your tunnel maps public domain → localhost:5000 (e.g., your ngrok domain).\par
- Share the domain (e.g., https://earlene-unrecognizable-vaughn.ngrok-free.dev).\par
- Your friend’s app replaces http://127.0.0.1:5000 with the public domain in all requests.\par
- CORS is enabled, so browser apps can call the APIs from a different origin.\par
\par
Example (remote cURL):\par
{\pard\li360\f0
curl -s -H "Content-Type: application/json" -X POST \\par
  -d '{"temperature":26.5,"rainfall":780,"season":"Rainy","soil_type":"Loam"}' \\par
  https://earlene-unrecognizable-vaughn.ngrok-free.dev/api/crop/recommend\par
}\par
\par
\b 6) Irrigation Decision Logic (Server + Arduino)\b0\par
- Sensor input from Arduino: DATA,<soil_moisture>,<temperature>,<humidity>\par
- Moisture thresholds (tunable):\par
  - DRY_SOIL_THRESHOLD: < 300 → DRY\par
  - WET_SOIL_THRESHOLD: ≥ 600 → WET\par
  - Edit at: water_harvest_dashboard.py lines 42–44 (also RETRY_WINDOW_SEC=30)\par
- Control output to Arduino: IRRIGATE | STOP | RAIN_ALERT + LED8_ON/OFF (pin 8).\par
- Guardrails:\par
  - Sensor override for safety: if soil is DRY, irrigate even if model says STOP.\par
  - Transition gating: ignore repeated IRRIGATE (send only on state change).\par
  - 30s retry: if still DRY after 30s from last IRRIGATE, re-send IRRIGATE.\par
\par
\b 7) Machine Learning – Irrigation Model\b0\par
Artifacts:\par
- models/irrigation_decision_model_REAL.pkl (classifier), models/model_info_REAL.json (feature schema).\par
Features: Soil_Moisture, Temperature_C, Humidity_Percent, Rain_Coming_Binary, Days_Since_Rain, Hour, Weather_Humidity, Weather_Temp_C.\par
Training data: engineered from irrigation logs (models/processed_irrigation_data.csv).\par
\par
\ul Performance (test split: 10 samples)\ul0\par
precision/recall/f1/support:\par
- IRRIGATE: 1.00 / 1.00 / 1.00 (support 2)\par
- STOP:     1.00 / 1.00 / 1.00 (support 8)\par
accuracy: 1.00\par
macro avg: precision 1.00 / recall 1.00 / f1 1.00 (support 10)\par
weighted avg: precision 1.00 / recall 1.00 / f1 1.00 (support 10)\par
\par
Runtime: builds features from live sensor + weather, predicts IRRIGATE/STOP, then applies safety override, transition gating, and 30s retry before sending the final command to Arduino.\par
\par
\b 8) Soil Health Analytics\b0\par
- Reads historical CSV, cleans timestamps, computes Soil_Health_Score vs ideal moisture (650).\par
- Detects faster-than-normal drying (>20% above historic).\par
- Alerts: TREND DETECTED, SOIL DEGRADATION (<40 score), MOISTURE CRITICAL (<300).\par
- Plotly visuals: last 7/30-day moisture, health score history.\par
- Farmer summary: traffic-light status, “Do now” action, reason, tips, and a simple guide describing the charts.\par
\par
\b 9) Crop Recommendation Engine\b0\par
- Synthetic Zambia-like dataset (models/crop_synthetic_dataset.csv).\par
- Trains models/crop_recommender.pkl if scikit-learn available; else uses rule-based scoring.\par
- API: POST /api/crop/recommend → ranked crops, best crop + risk assessment.\par
- Responsive UI at /crop-recommend (mobile-friendly form).\par
\par
\b 10) Security & Ops Notes\b0\par
- Consider moving weather API keys to environment variables in production.\par
- If exposing publicly, protect sensitive endpoints (/api/test/*) or add a simple token header (X-API-Key).\par
- For hardware reliability, use a separate motor power supply with common ground and flyback diode.\par
- Optionally cache weather (e.g., every 10–15 minutes) to reduce latency.\par
